## Building a Todo List in Angular

**Mental model:** A todo list is CRUD over an array of `{ id, text, done }`. Hold the list and the current filter as component fields; expose the visible todos and active count via getters so the template stays declarative. Classic `NgModule` setup — no signals/standalone, and no `?.`/`??` (the build rejects them).

### Step 1 — Model and add
```typescript
todos: Todo[] = [];
add(text: string): void {
  this.todos.push({ id: String(Date.now()), text, done: false });
}
```

### Step 2 — Toggle and delete
```typescript
toggle(t: Todo): void { t.done = !t.done; }
remove(id: string): void { this.todos = this.todos.filter((x) => x.id !== id); }
```

### Step 3 — Derive the view with getters
```typescript
get visible(): Todo[] {
  if (this.filter === 'active') { return this.todos.filter((t) => !t.done); }
  if (this.filter === 'completed') { return this.todos.filter((t) => t.done); }
  return this.todos;
}
get remaining(): number { return this.todos.filter((t) => !t.done).length; }
```

### Step 4 — Add from the template
Use a template reference for the input and clear it after adding (no `FormsModule`/`ngModel`).

```html
<form (submit)="onSubmit(box.value); box.value=''"><input #box /></form>
```

**Edge cases**

| Case | Handling |
| :-- | :-- |
| Empty text | Trim and skip in `onSubmit`. |
| `trackBy` | Track by `id` to avoid re-creating rows. |
| Filter drift | Getters derive — nothing to sync. |

**Interview tip:** Driving the input via a template reference variable (`#box`) instead of `ngModel` shows you can build forms without pulling in `FormsModule` — a nice fit for a small, dependency-free component.

